	<div class="spacer"></div>
	



			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3336">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Please accept the enclosed thirty-dollar check for a one-year subscription to your wonderful magazine. I hope you&rsquo;ll make sure I get Issue 182 so I don&rsquo;t miss the <a href="/article/993">next installment of Sparrow&rsquo;s adventures</a>.</p>

<p>I work in the magazine industry here in New York City, so I&rsquo;m always reading magazines I haven&rsquo;t tried before; it&rsquo;s rare that I&rsquo;m so thrilled by one. <strong>The Sun</strong> offers an unusual combination of artistic and intellectual rigor and spiritual depth. I don&rsquo;t remember the last time I read a magazine where so many stories <em>rang true</em>. Congratulations to your editor and the rest of your staff. I look forward to more.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Ariel Zeitlin<br>New York, New York</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3337">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I came home late last night after a retirement party for a friend. I was happy and tired. Your magazine was in the mail. Standing in my kitchen, I started to flip through it; I ended hunched over the counter for half an hour before I decided to make a cup of tea and read by the wood stove. I went to bed and read a bit more. And just now I woke up and finished the <a href="/article/985">first part of Sparrow&rsquo;s tale</a>.</p>

<p>Thank you for kind and gentle Sparrow, who made me laugh out loud; for <a href="/article/989">Ram Dass</a> and his humanness; for <a href="/article/986">Dan Barker&rsquo;s gardens</a>.</p>

<p>What a <em>great</em> magazine!</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Sue Walton<br>Alexander, North Carolina</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3338">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Concerning Sparrow&rsquo;s &ldquo;<a href="/article/985">Born Too Young: Diary of a Pilgrimage</a>&rdquo; [Issue 181], the tendency to depict women as objects permeates American culture. Disrespectful and demeaning messages about women are always disheartening and infuriating, but it is even more appalling to find such misogyny in one who praises himself as an enlightened and egalitarian &ldquo;thinker.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Why would Sparrow, who regards even a gnat&rsquo;s life as sacred, take such sadistic pleasure in his wife&rsquo;s &ldquo;frozen look of pain&rdquo;?</p>

<p>Sparrow spent time in a peace camp in Scotland protesting acts of aggression, and yet he never questions his own propensity for violence (&ldquo;.&nbsp;.&nbsp;. I&rsquo;ll hate her &mdash; smash in her face when I reach Dharamsala.&rdquo;)</p>

<p>The act of urinating on his wife is degrading to them both. How would he feel if the roles were reversed? Why does the <em>man</em> always violate the <em>woman</em>? Just reading the passage is humiliating.</p>

<p>So to Sparrow, the one who says women &ldquo;smell bad,&rdquo; we say, <em>you stink!</em> You wrote, &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve been meditating twelve years. I feel like I haven&rsquo;t made any progress.&rdquo; We agree. You haven&rsquo;t.</p>

<p>P.S. to the editors: Where was your judgment? What were you thinking? Please don&rsquo;t insult us by crying &ldquo;artistic expression.&rdquo; It is shocking enough that Sparrow wrote this rubbish, but it is even more shocking that you had the poor taste to publish it in your magazine of presumably <em>enlightened</em> ideas. If we&rsquo;d wanted to read sexist trash we&rsquo;d have bought a copy of <em>Hustler</em>. An explanation and apology to your female readers is in order.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Barbara and Ginia Stevenson<br>Memphis, Tennessee</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence-respond fill-pattern-light" id="3339">
								<p><a href="/contributors/sparrow"><strong>Sparrow</strong></a> responds:</p>
							<p>I&rsquo;ve always wanted to do this &mdash; to write a shrewd, devastating rebuttal to a letter writer, like they do in <em>The Village Voice</em>. Now, on a train from New York City to Staunton, Virginia, I may do so. The problem is, I agree with these letter writers; the whole thing is scandalous. (To make matters worse, my parents have a subscription to this magazine!) I think <strong>The Sun</strong> made a mistake printing it. Or I made a mistake writing it. Or perhaps my biggest mistake was living it. But I certainly didn&rsquo;t <em>intend</em> to live it. It was, like most life, something I backed into.</p>

<p>By the way, I spoke to Jeanne and she says I <em>begged</em> her to pee on me.</p>

<p>And when did I say I was enlightened? Huh? (Though I did grandly define &ldquo;karma&rdquo; and &ldquo;dharma.&rdquo;) Isn&rsquo;t that the point of the title, &ldquo;Born Too Young&rdquo;? That I, or everyone, is born twenty years too early, and by the time we&rsquo;re thirty-two we&rsquo;re dumb as a twelve-year-old?</p>

<p>Shouldn&rsquo;t we all be stopping this <em>war</em> instead of arguing like this?</p>

<p>We&rsquo;re switching from an electric to a diesel engine now in D.C. A boy in front of me who&rsquo;s about two has been saying, &ldquo;Choo choo,&rdquo; over and over for about three hours. Now his mother is tickling him and he&rsquo;s gurgle-laughing. He is cute and very boring, and I must publicly apologize to everyone I have cutely bored with my book.</p>

<p>My spiritual advisor, Dada Daneshanandaji, read the Stevensons&rsquo; letter, said, &ldquo;Uh oh,&rdquo; a number of times, and advised me, somewhat cryptically, to write a short response. I suppose he thinks I&rsquo;ll appear statesmanlike so that the Stevensons will seem hysterical. Well, I refuse to be statesmanlike! If anything, I will be more hysterical than they! I demand my own execution! I demand my writings be burned! I refuse to be level-headed about this!</p>
	</div>


								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3325">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>As for Sparrow [&ldquo;Born Too Young,&rdquo; Issues 181-183], well, Buddhists ain&rsquo;t Buddha, and Christians ain&rsquo;t Christ, and it&rsquo;s good to be reminded of the mess we all have to work through. Religion is human, and it doesn&rsquo;t exclude men who piss on women <em>and</em> acknowledge the pain of it. Denial&rsquo;s illusion, ain&rsquo;t it? Thank you for letting us remember that the proto-saint is crawling up through mounds of rottenness and shit, not standing there by the microwave holding a vacuum cleaner with a self-righteous smile. Sparrow is an honest man, and so he gives other folks the willies.</p>

<p>&ldquo;<a href="/article/985">Born Too Young: Diary of a Pilgrimage (Part One)</a>&rdquo; [Issue 181]</p>

<p>&ldquo;<a href="/article/993">Born Too Young: Diary of a Pilgrimage (Part Two)</a>&rdquo; [Issue 182]</p>

<p>&ldquo;<a href="/article/1005">Born Too Young: Diary of a Pilgrimage (Part Three)</a>&rdquo; [Issue 183]</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Bill Piper<br>Altoona, Pennsylvania</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3326">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I have a message for Sparrow: don&rsquo;t be discouraged by the criticism. I am a woman of fifty-one and my perspective is not as harsh. Your critics exhibit truth but no humor. I loved your travel installments, and when I read your travails with Jeanne, I thought, &ldquo;Oh, dear, Sparrow has some way to go with women &mdash; he&rsquo;s blowing it bad.&rdquo; But I also feel that your questing soul will mature &mdash; eventually, the pain of unconsidered action will bore you. At least you had the courage to be uncomfortably honest about the angry confusions in your heart.</p>

<p>Your literary style is unique and fresh, and your sense of humor off-the-wall wondrous.</p>

<p>Go elsewhere and give us some more adventures!</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Leslie Lindborg<br>Point Arena, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3327">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Thanks, Sparrow, for your courage, or stupidity, in letting it all hang out. You don&rsquo;t seem to hold too many illusions about yourself &mdash; you write as you honestly experience, and there are few people who can do that.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Diane Moore<br>Rochester, Michigan</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3328">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I love <strong>The Sun</strong>. I can even put up with some of the interviews you run just to read Sparrow. Sadly, what other magazine would publish him? Can you see a spread in <em>People</em>: &ldquo;Likable Eccentric Says: I Was Born Too Young&rdquo;? No. <em>No.</em></p>

<p>Do you ever talk to him? Or does he just leave a big sloppy Bic-written manuscript on your doorstep and vanish? I picture him as a little wisp of steam rising off the concrete. I love his writing. It&rsquo;s one of the few spiritual journeys I&rsquo;ve read that sounds like a real spiritual journey: confusing, frustrating, grubby, with irritating people and enough sex to drive everyone crazy. Keep publishing that man. I&rsquo;ll buy his book when it comes out. I&rsquo;ll buy a bunch and give &rsquo;em as gifts. I&rsquo;ll make the single good bookstore in Texas order a crate. If he comes to Dallas I&rsquo;ll buy him macrobiotic enchiladas.</p>

<p>Read some of your readers&rsquo; letters .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. some of them just smoking mad. Why on earth would anyone take offense at your magazine? Are these folks just crouched and quivering like Dobermans <em>looking</em> to be pissed off? <strong>The Sun</strong> is a flashlight in a dark time.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author"><a href="/contributors/ashley-walker">Ashley Walker</a><br>Dallas, Texas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3329">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I was amused by the uproar caused by Sparrow. I have to say I was surprised that he peed on his wife, and even more surprised that he told everyone about it and then included his picture. So he makes a lousy traveling companion. He laid trips on his wife and made her meditate and made her practice monogamy and thought she was an idiot. But that&rsquo;s the point &mdash; we think we&rsquo;re doing one thing, we think we&rsquo;re on the road to Enlightenment, but really we&rsquo;re being assholes. His jealousy, his dependency, his fears &mdash; these were weaknesses that he was revealing to us. How can people be insulted by that? I was not demeaned, disheartened, infuriated, humiliated, or violated by his words. I credit anybody who can write such things in a magazine read by his parents.</p>

<p>I was also surprised by the criticism of Hella Hammid&rsquo;s cover photograph [<a href="/issues/182">Issue 182</a>] of the pregnant belly. I&rsquo;ve been pregnant, and I&rsquo;ve worked with midwives; it never occurred to me that you might be trying to degrade women or pregnancy by using that photograph.</p>

<p>If there&rsquo;s a problem, it doesn&rsquo;t rest with the fact that Sparrow wasn&rsquo;t nice to his wife, or with Hella Hammid&rsquo;s photograph, but with the response they received. Our culture has produced people who can&rsquo;t tolerate the feel of natural textures, the scent of natural smells &mdash; people who create artificial worlds in which to insulate themselves, who can&rsquo;t tolerate natural images, who can&rsquo;t tolerate stories about the human condition. It&rsquo;s all the same can of worms, as far as I can tell.</p>

<p>I hope you continue to resist the &ldquo;correct&rdquo; line; I hope you continue to offend the true believers. I hope you keep giving us Sparrow&rsquo;s stuff.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author"><a href="/contributors/alison-clement">Alison Clement</a><br>Yachats, Oregon</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

